title: Human Resource Management in Small Businesses
description:
Students will gain an understanding of the human resource management function in the context of the small business. Emphasis is placed on strategies employed by small business owners to address shifts in workforce demographics, professional expectations, legal requirements, and contemporary workforce issues.
Prereq: Jr standing.

title: Economics of Public Policy Analysis
description:
Understanding of economic tools and concepts for analyzing public policies important to the food industry, agriculture and natural resources.
Prereq: 2001 or 2001H or Econ 2001 or 2001H; and AEDEcon 3000. Prereq or concur: 4001 or Econ 4001.02.

title: Data Analysis for Agribusiness and Applied Economics
description:
Introductory course in data analysis, stressing computer applications of probability and statistics, problems of data gathering, presentation, and interpretation in economics and business.
Prereq: Math 1130 (130) or 1131 (131) or 1148 (148) or 1150 (150) or 1151.01 (151.01) or 1151.02 (151.02) or 1156 (151.03). Not open to students with credit for 2005 (205) or ComLdr 3537 (AgrEduc 387 or AEE 387) or HCS 2260 (260) or AnimSci 2260 (260) or Stat 1430 (133) or 1450 (145). GE data anly course. GE foundation math and quant reasoning or data anyl course.

title: Economics of Public Policy Analysis
description:
Understanding of economic tools and concepts for analyzing public policies important to the food industry, agriculture and natural resources.
Prereq: 2001 or 2001H or Econ 2001 or 2001H; and AEDEcon 3000. Prereq or concur: 4001 or Econ 4001.02.

title: Introduction to Sustainability
description:
Introduces students to principles from various disciplines related to social, economic and environmental sustainability. Students will evaluate key concepts and examine tradeoffs that are a part of sustainability action using case studies representing diverse perspectives. Team-taught course with faculty member in ENR.
Prereq: Not open to students with credit for 2500, ENR 2500, or ENR 2501. GE theme sustainability course, High-Impact Practice Interdisciplinary and Integrated Collaborative Teaching. Cross-listed in ENR.

title: Energy, the Environment, and the Economy
description:
Understand the role of energy in the economy and the environment. Explore the economics of clean, renewable energy, and understand the different policies for pollution control.
Prereq: 2001 (200), Econ 2001.01, 2001.02, or 2001.03 (200). Not open to students with credit for 565 or IntStds 4320 (565). Cross-listed in IntStds 4320.

title: Regional Economics and Sustainable Growth
description:
Designed to study theories and methodologies for analyzing rural and regional economic development, primarily in advanced economies.
Prereq: 2001 (200), or equiv course in Microeconomics.

title: Food Security and Globalization
description:
Examination of the causes of and solutions for food insecurity. Global and local factors that affect access to food are also considered.
Prereq: 2001 (200) or Econ 2001 (200), or permission of instructor. Not open to students with credit for 434 or 532, or IntStds 4532 or 434. Cross-listed in IntStds.

title: Food, Population, and the Environment
description:
Issues related to world-wide population increases, food production, and associated environmental stress; policy options for lessening these concerns, especially in low-income countries.
Prereq: Jr or Sr standing. Not open to students with credit for 597.01, 4597.01H (597.01H), IntStds 4597.01 (597.01), or 4597.01H (597.01H). GE cross-disciplinary seminar course. Cross-listed in IntStds.

title: Principles of Agribusiness and Food Supply Chains
description:
Study of the actors, intrinsic issues and support systems that are essential to make agribusiness, commodity and food supply chains effective.
Prereq: 2001 or Econ 2001.

title: Strategic Management
description:
Experiential learning and managerial economics applied to strategic management in agribusiness. Formulate managerial strategies in a competitive environment constrained by the firm's products, internal resources, market segments, and supply chains.
Prereq: 3101 (401), 3103 (403), and 4001 (500), and a second writing course. Not open to students with credit for 601.

title: Environmental and Natural Resources Economics
description:
This introductory course in environmental and natural resource economics provides an economic perspective to analyze contemporary issues in environmental protection and natural resource management.
Prereq: 2001 or Econ 2001.

title: The Sustainable Economy: Concepts and Methods
description:
Introduces students to core concepts of sustainability in economics and the quantitative methods necessary to understand and evaluate sustainable development.
Prereq: 4310 and ENR 3900, or permission of instructor.

title: Salesmanship in Agribusiness and Agriculture
description:
Principles and techniques of selling to agribusiness buyers.
Prereq: Not open for students with credit for BusTec 2232T.

title: Principles of Agribusiness Marketing
description:
Study of specific problems of marketing food and fiber products with emphasis on structures and institutions facing agribusinesses in domestic and international markets.
Prereq: 2001 (200), 2001H (200H), Econ 2001 (200), or 2001H (201H). Not open to students with credit for 402.

title: Project Management for Sustainability and Applied Economics
description: An introduction to project management concepts and techniques focusing on how to initiate, plan, manage, control, and close projects related to sustainability and applied economics.

title: Agribusiness Law
description:
A study of the legal system and selected areas of law that affect agricultural types of businesses, including civil liabilities, property law, business law and regulatory law.
Prereq: 2001 (200), 2001H (200H), Econ 2001 (200), or 2001H (201H). Not open to students with credit for 470 or 670.

title: Assessing Sustainability: Project Experience
description:
Students gain experience in sustainability assessment by applying concepts and quantitative methods to evaluate environmental, economic, social & technical sustainability of specific projects. EEDS major capstone. Co-taught by ENR/AEDE faculty.
Prereq: 2500, or 2501/2501E, or ENR 2500 or 2501/2501E, and Sr standing; or permission of instructor. Not open to students with credit for ENR 4567. Cross-listed in ENR.

title: Diversity in the Workplace: Challenges and Opportunities
description:
The purpose of this course is to examine how and why diversity affects interpersonal and intergroup interactions in organizations, to develop an understanding of what diversity means, and to explore contemporary organizational strategies for managing workplace diversity while working to better understand what we as individuals bring to the dynamic.
GE diversity soc div in the US course.

title: Individual Studies in Agribusiness and Applied Economics
description:
Planning, conducting, and reporting a special problem in agricultural economics.
Prereq: CPHR 2.50 or above, and permission of instructor. Not open to students with 6 cr hrs in 4193 or 693.01-693.08. Repeatable to a maximum of 6 cr hrs or 3 completions. This course is graded S/U.

title: Managerial Economics for Agribusiness
description:
Application of economic theory and methods to agribusiness decision making.
Prereq: 3000, and 2001 or 2001H or Econ 2001 or 2001H.

title: Analytics for Agribusiness and Applied Economics
description:
Students will be introduced to and gain experience with quantitative statistical models and related analytical methods and their application to food, agricultural, and environmental systems. There is an emphasis on real world application and presentation of the results.
Prereq: 2005, or AnimSci 2260, or ComLdr 3537 or Stat 1450.xx; or permission of instructor.

title: Food, Population, and the Environment
description:
Issues related to world-wide population increases, food production, and associated environmental stress; policy options for lessening these concerns, especially in low-income countries.
Prereq: Jr or Sr standing. Not open to students with credit for 597.01, 4597.01H (597.01H), IntStds 4597.01 (597.01), or 4597.01H (597.01H). GE cross-disciplinary seminar course. Cross-listed in IntStds.

title: Analytics for Agribusiness and Applied Economics
description:
Students will be introduced to and gain experience with quantitative statistical models and related analytical methods and their application to food, agricultural, and environmental systems. There is an emphasis on real world application and presentation of the results.
Prereq: 2005, or AnimSci 2260, or ComLdr 3537 or Stat 1450.xx; or permission of instructor.

description:
Introduces students to principles from various disciplines related to social, economic and environmental sustainability. Students will evaluate key concepts and examine tradeoffs that are a part of sustainability action using case studies representing diverse perspectives. Team-taught course with faculty member in ENR.
Prereq: Not open to students with credit for 2500, ENR 2500, or ENR 2501. GE theme sustainability course, High-Impact Practice Interdisciplinary and Integrated Collaborative Teaching. Cross-listed in ENR.

title: Exploring Sustainability: SUSTAINS LC Seminar
description:
Designed for SUSTAINS Learning Community students to explore their interests within sustainability, learn about opportunities to be involved in campus and local community sustainability efforts, and connect with campus partners and faculty working and researching in the field. Students must be a part of the SUSTAINS Learning Community in order to take this seminar.
Prereq: Must be in the SUSTAINS Learning Community. This course is graded S/U. Cross-listed in ENR.

Prerequisites: Must be in the SUSTAINS Learning Community

title: Commodity Futures and Options Markets
description:
This course covers the relevant aspects of the futures and options and underlying cash markets focusing mostly on physical commodities but also on financial instruments such as treasuries and equity securities.
Prereq: 2001 or Econ 2001.01 or 2001.03H.

title: Individual Studies in Agribusiness and Applied Economics
description:
Planning, conducting, and reporting a special problem in agricultural economics.
Prereq: CPHR 2.50 or above, and permission of instructor. Not open to students with 6 cr hrs in 4193 or 693.01-693.08. Repeatable to a maximum of 6 cr hrs or 3 completions. This course is graded S/U.

title: Emerging Issues in Agribusiness and Applied Economics
description:
This course familiarizes students with emerging domestic and international issues relevant to professionals in agribusiness through the lens of applied economics, while improving their teamwork and communications skills.
Prereq: Jr standing.

title: Principles of Food and Resource Economics
description:
Microeconomic principles applied to allocation issues in the production, distribution, and consumption of food and natural resource use.
Prereq: Not open to students with credit for 2001H or Econ 2001. This course is available for EM credit. GE soc sci human, nat, and econ resources course. GE foundation social and behavioral sci course.

title: Managerial Records and Analysis
description:
Nature and need for business records, analysis and interpretation of essential records from manager/owner viewpoint; their use in small business practices.
Prereq: 2001 or 2001H or Econ 2001.01, 2001.02, or 2001.03H. Not open to students with credit for AcctMIS 2200 or 2300.

title: Principles of Agribusiness Finance
description:
Financial management of agribusinesses: financial system, time value of money, security valuation, capital budgeting, capital structure, portfolio analysis, financial institutions, futures and options contracts. 
Prereq: 2001 (200), 2001H (200H), Econ 2001 (200), or 2001H (201H); and AEDEcon 2105 (412) or AcctMIS 2200 (211); and AEDEcon 2005 (205), AEE 387, AnimSci 2260 (260), ComLdr 3537, HCS 2260 (260), Stat 1430 (133), or 1450 (145). Not open to students with credit for 403.

title: Principles of Agribusiness Management
description:
Introduction to agribusiness management principles and skills in the context of the four functions of management: planning, organizing, directing, and controlling.
Prereq: 2001 (200) or 2001H (201H) or Econ 2001 (200) or 2001H (200H). Not open to students with credit for 401.
